Title: Bánh Canh Cua 87 Trần khắc Chân Quận 1
Bánh Mì Hòa Mã
Note:
A beautiful alternative to the banh mi sandwich is a Vietnamese dish called op la, or eggs cooked in a littler personal pan, often supplemented by slices of meat like ham, onions, and served with those wonderful crusty Vietnamese baguettes.

Just like some other dishes on this blog, op la offers a bit of a fusion of Vietnamese and Western ingredients and cooking methods, all blended into a single meal.

Title: Hủ Tiếu Nam Vang Thành Đạt
Cafe Vy
Note: Vy Cà Phê is a traditional coffee shop that has been around for 60 years. You will get to try the dripping style coffee (cà phê phin) on a low-sitting chair, which is perfectly local style.

Title: Hủ tíu mì Cật
Note: This store has opened since 1960s. It's a traditional pork kidney noodle store, located very near to Ben Thanh Market!

Title: Cô Giang
Note:
This street is full of cheap and delicious street food and is located very near to our homestay. I must say it's not for tourists with weak stomach, but if you're adventurous, you should try some awesome local dishes such as:
 Bò lá lốp – grilled beef in betel leaf – many stores on Cô Giang street.
 Há cảo , sủi cáo – Vietnamese dumplings – 57 Đề Thám street.
 Bột chiên – a little bit similar to Carrot cake in Singapore, you eat together with sunny-side-up
egg, and green papaya salad – 133 Cô Bắc street.
